</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">Diffusion-weighted (DW) imaging is an emerging technique in body imaging that provides indirect information about the microenvironment of tissues and lesions and helps detect, characterize, and follow up abnormalities. Two main challenges in the application of DW imaging to body imaging are the decreased signal-to-noise ratio of body tissues compared with neuronal tissues due to their shorter T2 relaxation time, and image degradation related to physiologic motion (eg, respiratory motion). Use of smaller <i>b</i> values and newer motion compensation techniques allow the evaluation of anatomic structures with DW imaging. DW imaging can be performed as a breath-hold sequence or a free-breathing sequence with or without respiratory triggering. Depending on the mobility of water molecules in their microenvironment, different normal tissues have different signals at DW imaging. Some normal tissues (eg, lymph nodes, spleen, ovarian and testicular parenchyma) are diffusion restricted, whereas others (eg, gallbladder, corpora cavernosa, endometrium, cartilage) show T2 shine-through. Epiphyses that contain fatty marrow and bone cortex appear dark on both DW images and apparent diffusion coefficient maps. Current and emerging applications of DW imaging in pediatric body imaging include tumor detection and characterization, assessment of therapy response and monitoring of tumors, noninvasive detection and grading of liver fibrosis and cirrhosis, detection of abscesses, and evaluation of inflammatory bowel disease.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2014</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.343135047">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.343135047">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig1.jpeg" height="1511" width="2500" aria-labelledby="fig1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 1</span> Diffusion mechanism. Diagram <i>A</i> illustrates a microenvironment with restricted mobility of water molecules due to a greater number of cells, intact cell membranes, distended cells, reduced extracellular spaces, and large molecules. Diagram <i>B</i> illustrates a microenvironment with increased mobility of water molecules due to a lesser number of cells, damaged cell membranes, enlarged extracellular spaces, and absence of large molecules.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig2.jpeg" height="374" width="1800" aria-labelledby="fig2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 2</span> Diffusion weighting. T2-weighted images are made diffusion weighted by applying diffusion gradient <i>(DG)</i> pulses before and after the 180° radiofrequency pulse <i>(RFp)</i>. The <i>b</i> value (in seconds per square millimeter) depends on and increases with amplitude, duration of application, and separation of diffusion gradients.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig3" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig3.jpeg" height="652" width="900" aria-labelledby="fig3" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 3</span> Plexiform neurofibroma in a 3-year-old girl. DWIBS image of the brachial plexus displayed with an inverted gray scale shows thick, enlarged nerve roots on the left side (arrow) in keeping with plexiform neurofibroma. The spinal cord <i>(C)</i>, palatine tonsils <i>(T)</i>, cervical lymph nodes (arrowheads), and thymus <i>(Th)</i>, as well as the red marrow in the ribs and upper humeri, show signal because they are normally diffusion restricted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig3">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig4a.jpeg" height="668" width="936" aria-labelledby="fig4a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4a</span> Qualitative DW imaging assessment of a pancreatic neoplasm in a 16-year-old girl. Axial fat-saturated T2-weighted magnetic resonance (MR) image <b>(a)</b>, DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b>, ADC map <b>(c)</b>, and exponential ADC map <b>(d)</b> show a solid pseudopapillary epithelial neoplasm of the pancreas. The solid anterior component of the tumor (arrows) shows diffusion restriction with bright signal on the DW image, turns dark on the ADC map, and remains hyperintense on the exponential ADC map. The posterolateral cystic component (arrowhead) is not diffusion restricted and is dark on the DW image, heterogeneously dark on the ADC map, and heterogeneously bright on the exponential ADC map due to susceptibility artifact caused by hemorrhage within the component.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig4a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig4b.jpeg" height="668" width="939" aria-labelledby="fig4b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4b</span> Qualitative DW imaging assessment of a pancreatic neoplasm in a 16-year-old girl. Axial fat-saturated T2-weighted magnetic resonance (MR) image <b>(a)</b>, DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b>, ADC map <b>(c)</b>, and exponential ADC map <b>(d)</b> show a solid pseudopapillary epithelial neoplasm of the pancreas. The solid anterior component of the tumor (arrows) shows diffusion restriction with bright signal on the DW image, turns dark on the ADC map, and remains hyperintense on the exponential ADC map. The posterolateral cystic component (arrowhead) is not diffusion restricted and is dark on the DW image, heterogeneously dark on the ADC map, and heterogeneously bright on the exponential ADC map due to susceptibility artifact caused by hemorrhage within the component.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig4b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig4c.jpeg" height="639" width="932" aria-labelledby="fig4c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4c</span> Qualitative DW imaging assessment of a pancreatic neoplasm in a 16-year-old girl. Axial fat-saturated T2-weighted magnetic resonance (MR) image <b>(a)</b>, DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b>, ADC map <b>(c)</b>, and exponential ADC map <b>(d)</b> show a solid pseudopapillary epithelial neoplasm of the pancreas. The solid anterior component of the tumor (arrows) shows diffusion restriction with bright signal on the DW image, turns dark on the ADC map, and remains hyperintense on the exponential ADC map. The posterolateral cystic component (arrowhead) is not diffusion restricted and is dark on the DW image, heterogeneously dark on the ADC map, and heterogeneously bright on the exponential ADC map due to susceptibility artifact caused by hemorrhage within the component.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig4c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig4d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig4d.jpeg" height="639" width="942" aria-labelledby="fig4d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 4d</span> Qualitative DW imaging assessment of a pancreatic neoplasm in a 16-year-old girl. Axial fat-saturated T2-weighted magnetic resonance (MR) image <b>(a)</b>, DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b>, ADC map <b>(c)</b>, and exponential ADC map <b>(d)</b> show a solid pseudopapillary epithelial neoplasm of the pancreas. The solid anterior component of the tumor (arrows) shows diffusion restriction with bright signal on the DW image, turns dark on the ADC map, and remains hyperintense on the exponential ADC map. The posterolateral cystic component (arrowhead) is not diffusion restricted and is dark on the DW image, heterogeneously dark on the ADC map, and heterogeneously bright on the exponential ADC map due to susceptibility artifact caused by hemorrhage within the component.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig4d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig5a.jpeg" height="676" width="909" aria-labelledby="fig5a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5a</span> Normal signal of upper abdominal structures at DW imaging in a 16-year-old girl. Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(a)</b> and ADC map <b>(b)</b> show normal upper abdominal structures. The spleen <i>(Sp)</i> and spinal cord (arrow) show diffusion restriction, the gallbladder <i>(GB)</i> shows T2 shine-through, and the kidneys <i>(K)</i> have a high T2 relaxation time and high ADC suggestive of T2 shine-through, albeit to a lesser degree than the gallbladder. The normal liver <i>(L)</i> and pancreas <i>(P)</i> have low T2 signal and moderate ADC and therefore appear isointense on both images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig5a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig5b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig5b.jpeg" height="675" width="966" aria-labelledby="fig5b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 5b</span> Normal signal of upper abdominal structures at DW imaging in a 16-year-old girl. Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(a)</b> and ADC map <b>(b)</b> show normal upper abdominal structures. The spleen <i>(Sp)</i> and spinal cord (arrow) show diffusion restriction, the gallbladder <i>(GB)</i> shows T2 shine-through, and the kidneys <i>(K)</i> have a high T2 relaxation time and high ADC suggestive of T2 shine-through, albeit to a lesser degree than the gallbladder. The normal liver <i>(L)</i> and pancreas <i>(P)</i> have low T2 signal and moderate ADC and therefore appear isointense on both images.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig5b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig6a.jpeg" height="641" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig6a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6a</span> Normal signal of the small bowel at DW imaging in an 11-year-old girl with no bowel abnormalities. <b>(a)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows normal jejunal loops with hyperintense signal (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows normal ileal loops with complete signal loss (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Single-shot T2-weighted MR image obtained at the same level as <b>b</b> shows normally distended ileal loops (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig6a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig6b.jpeg" height="673" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig6b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6b</span> Normal signal of the small bowel at DW imaging in an 11-year-old girl with no bowel abnormalities. <b>(a)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows normal jejunal loops with hyperintense signal (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows normal ileal loops with complete signal loss (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Single-shot T2-weighted MR image obtained at the same level as <b>b</b> shows normally distended ileal loops (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig6b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig6c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig6c.jpeg" height="673" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig6c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 6c</span> Normal signal of the small bowel at DW imaging in an 11-year-old girl with no bowel abnormalities. <b>(a)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows normal jejunal loops with hyperintense signal (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) shows normal ileal loops with complete signal loss (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Single-shot T2-weighted MR image obtained at the same level as <b>b</b> shows normally distended ileal loops (arrows).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig6c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig7a.jpeg" height="615" width="850" aria-labelledby="fig7a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7a</span> Normal signal of the uterus and ovaries at DW imaging in a 16-year-old girl. Axial DW images (<i>b</i> = 0 [<b>a</b>] and 800 [<b>b</b>] sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) and ADC map <b>(c)</b> show a normal uterus and ovaries (<i>LO</i> = left ovary, <i>RO</i> = right ovary). The normal endometrium (<sub><b>*</b></sub>) shows T2 shine-through. The junctional zone (arrow) remains dark on <b>a</b>–<b>c</b>, a finding that indicates the presence of proton-poor connective tissue. The ovarian stroma shows diffusion restriction, whereas the follicles are not diffusion restricted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig7a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig7b.jpeg" height="670" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig7b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7b</span> Normal signal of the uterus and ovaries at DW imaging in a 16-year-old girl. Axial DW images (<i>b</i> = 0 [<b>a</b>] and 800 [<b>b</b>] sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) and ADC map <b>(c)</b> show a normal uterus and ovaries (<i>LO</i> = left ovary, <i>RO</i> = right ovary). The normal endometrium (<sub><b>*</b></sub>) shows T2 shine-through. The junctional zone (arrow) remains dark on <b>a</b>–<b>c</b>, a finding that indicates the presence of proton-poor connective tissue. The ovarian stroma shows diffusion restriction, whereas the follicles are not diffusion restricted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig7b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig7c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig7c.jpeg" height="670" width="838" aria-labelledby="fig7c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 7c</span> Normal signal of the uterus and ovaries at DW imaging in a 16-year-old girl. Axial DW images (<i>b</i> = 0 [<b>a</b>] and 800 [<b>b</b>] sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) and ADC map <b>(c)</b> show a normal uterus and ovaries (<i>LO</i> = left ovary, <i>RO</i> = right ovary). The normal endometrium (<sub><b>*</b></sub>) shows T2 shine-through. The junctional zone (arrow) remains dark on <b>a</b>–<b>c</b>, a finding that indicates the presence of proton-poor connective tissue. The ovarian stroma shows diffusion restriction, whereas the follicles are not diffusion restricted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig7c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig8a.jpeg" height="651" width="843" aria-labelledby="fig8a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8a</span> Normal signal of the testes and penis at DW imaging in a 17-year-old boy. Sagittal DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(a)</b> and ADC map <b>(b)</b> show normal corpora cavernosa (arrows) and testes (arrowheads). The corpora cavernosa show T2 shine-through, whereas the testes show normal diffusion restriction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig8a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig8b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig8b.jpeg" height="651" width="832" aria-labelledby="fig8b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 8b</span> Normal signal of the testes and penis at DW imaging in a 17-year-old boy. Sagittal DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(a)</b> and ADC map <b>(b)</b> show normal corpora cavernosa (arrows) and testes (arrowheads). The corpora cavernosa show T2 shine-through, whereas the testes show normal diffusion restriction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig8b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig9a.jpeg" height="814" width="803" aria-labelledby="fig9a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9a</span> Normal signal of muscles and bones at DW imaging in an 11-year-old girl. Coronal DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(a)</b> and ADC map <b>(b)</b> show normal skeletal muscles and bones. The skeletal muscles (arrowheads = psoas muscles) have low signal intensity on the DW image and become slightly bright on the ADC map. The red marrow in the vertebral bodies, iliac bones, and femoral necks (arrows) is bright on the DW image and dark on the ADC map, findings that indicate diffusion restriction, whereas the femoral epiphyses (<sub><b>*</b></sub>) are dark on both.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig9a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig9b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig9b.jpeg" height="814" width="772" aria-labelledby="fig9b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 9b</span> Normal signal of muscles and bones at DW imaging in an 11-year-old girl. Coronal DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(a)</b> and ADC map <b>(b)</b> show normal skeletal muscles and bones. The skeletal muscles (arrowheads = psoas muscles) have low signal intensity on the DW image and become slightly bright on the ADC map. The red marrow in the vertebral bodies, iliac bones, and femoral necks (arrows) is bright on the DW image and dark on the ADC map, findings that indicate diffusion restriction, whereas the femoral epiphyses (<sub><b>*</b></sub>) are dark on both.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig9b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig10a.jpeg" height="928" width="549" aria-labelledby="fig10a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10a</span> Normal signal of cartilage and marrow at DW imaging in a 3-year-old girl. Coronal T1-weighted MR image <b>(a)</b>, DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b>, and ADC map <b>(c)</b> show a normal knee joint. Unossified epiphyseal cartilage (arrows) is bright on both the DW image and the ADC map, indicating T2 shine-through. The ossified central epiphysis (<sub><b>*</b></sub>), which contains fatty marrow, is dark on both the DW image and the ADC map. The red marrow at the metaphyseal margin (arrowhead) is diffusion restricted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig10a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig10b.jpeg" height="928" width="589" aria-labelledby="fig10b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10b</span> Normal signal of cartilage and marrow at DW imaging in a 3-year-old girl. Coronal T1-weighted MR image <b>(a)</b>, DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b>, and ADC map <b>(c)</b> show a normal knee joint. Unossified epiphyseal cartilage (arrows) is bright on both the DW image and the ADC map, indicating T2 shine-through. The ossified central epiphysis (<sub><b>*</b></sub>), which contains fatty marrow, is dark on both the DW image and the ADC map. The red marrow at the metaphyseal margin (arrowhead) is diffusion restricted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig10b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig10c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig10c.jpeg" height="928" width="512" aria-labelledby="fig10c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 10c</span> Normal signal of cartilage and marrow at DW imaging in a 3-year-old girl. Coronal T1-weighted MR image <b>(a)</b>, DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b>, and ADC map <b>(c)</b> show a normal knee joint. Unossified epiphyseal cartilage (arrows) is bright on both the DW image and the ADC map, indicating T2 shine-through. The ossified central epiphysis (<sub><b>*</b></sub>), which contains fatty marrow, is dark on both the DW image and the ADC map. The red marrow at the metaphyseal margin (arrowhead) is diffusion restricted.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig10c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig11a.jpeg" height="638" width="937" aria-labelledby="fig11a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11a</span> Liver lesion detection with low <i>b</i>-value DW imaging in an 11-year-old boy with a history of undifferentiated renal sarcoma. Axial T2-weighted image <b>(a)</b> and DW image (<i>b</i> = 100 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b> show multiple variable-sized metastatic lesions in the liver (arrows). More lesions are seen, and the lesions are much better appreciated, on the DW image than on the T2-weighted image because of darkening of the vessels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig11a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig11b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig11b.jpeg" height="638" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig11b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 11b</span> Liver lesion detection with low <i>b</i>-value DW imaging in an 11-year-old boy with a history of undifferentiated renal sarcoma. Axial T2-weighted image <b>(a)</b> and DW image (<i>b</i> = 100 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b> show multiple variable-sized metastatic lesions in the liver (arrows). More lesions are seen, and the lesions are much better appreciated, on the DW image than on the T2-weighted image because of darkening of the vessels.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig11b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig12a.jpeg" height="688" width="848" aria-labelledby="fig12a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12a</span> Liver lesion characterization with DW imaging. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(a)</b> and ADC map <b>(b)</b> obtained in an 11-year-old boy show a large hepatoblastoma with restricted diffusion (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(c)</b> and ADC map <b>(d)</b> obtained in a 17-year-old girl show focal nodular hyperplasia in the liver (arrows). The lesion is bright on the DW image and remains slightly bright on the ADC map, findings that indicate intermediate diffusion. Splenic cysts with increased diffusion are also noted (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig12a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig12b.jpeg" height="688" width="827" aria-labelledby="fig12b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12b</span> Liver lesion characterization with DW imaging. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(a)</b> and ADC map <b>(b)</b> obtained in an 11-year-old boy show a large hepatoblastoma with restricted diffusion (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(c)</b> and ADC map <b>(d)</b> obtained in a 17-year-old girl show focal nodular hyperplasia in the liver (arrows). The lesion is bright on the DW image and remains slightly bright on the ADC map, findings that indicate intermediate diffusion. Splenic cysts with increased diffusion are also noted (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig12b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig12c.jpeg" height="575" width="831" aria-labelledby="fig12c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12c</span> Liver lesion characterization with DW imaging. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(a)</b> and ADC map <b>(b)</b> obtained in an 11-year-old boy show a large hepatoblastoma with restricted diffusion (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(c)</b> and ADC map <b>(d)</b> obtained in a 17-year-old girl show focal nodular hyperplasia in the liver (arrows). The lesion is bright on the DW image and remains slightly bright on the ADC map, findings that indicate intermediate diffusion. Splenic cysts with increased diffusion are also noted (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig12c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig12d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig12d.jpeg" height="575" width="844" aria-labelledby="fig12d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 12d</span> Liver lesion characterization with DW imaging. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(a)</b> and ADC map <b>(b)</b> obtained in an 11-year-old boy show a large hepatoblastoma with restricted diffusion (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(c)</b> and ADC map <b>(d)</b> obtained in a 17-year-old girl show focal nodular hyperplasia in the liver (arrows). The lesion is bright on the DW image and remains slightly bright on the ADC map, findings that indicate intermediate diffusion. Splenic cysts with increased diffusion are also noted (arrowhead).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig12d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig13a.jpeg" height="704" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig13a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13a</span> Evaluation of hepatic fibrosis and cirrhosis with DW imaging in a 5-year-old boy with a history of right hepatic lobe resection for hepatoblastoma. Axial postcontrast portal venous phase dynamic T1-weighted high-resolution isotropic volume examination (THRIVE) image (Philips Medical Systems, Best, the Netherlands) <b>(a)</b>, DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b>, and ADC map <b>(c)</b> show changes of cirrhosis in the residual liver. The hepatic parenchyma shows heterogeneous enhancement on the THRIVE image and higher signal intensity than is typical for normal liver on the DW image. On the ADC map, the hepatic parenchyma turns dark to a similar degree as the spleen <i>(Spl)</i>, a finding that suggests diffusion restriction reflecting cirrhotic changes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig13a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig13b.jpeg" height="727" width="931" aria-labelledby="fig13b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13b</span> Evaluation of hepatic fibrosis and cirrhosis with DW imaging in a 5-year-old boy with a history of right hepatic lobe resection for hepatoblastoma. Axial postcontrast portal venous phase dynamic T1-weighted high-resolution isotropic volume examination (THRIVE) image (Philips Medical Systems, Best, the Netherlands) <b>(a)</b>, DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b>, and ADC map <b>(c)</b> show changes of cirrhosis in the residual liver. The hepatic parenchyma shows heterogeneous enhancement on the THRIVE image and higher signal intensity than is typical for normal liver on the DW image. On the ADC map, the hepatic parenchyma turns dark to a similar degree as the spleen <i>(Spl)</i>, a finding that suggests diffusion restriction reflecting cirrhotic changes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig13b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig13c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig13c.jpeg" height="727" width="944" aria-labelledby="fig13c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 13c</span> Evaluation of hepatic fibrosis and cirrhosis with DW imaging in a 5-year-old boy with a history of right hepatic lobe resection for hepatoblastoma. Axial postcontrast portal venous phase dynamic T1-weighted high-resolution isotropic volume examination (THRIVE) image (Philips Medical Systems, Best, the Netherlands) <b>(a)</b>, DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b>, and ADC map <b>(c)</b> show changes of cirrhosis in the residual liver. The hepatic parenchyma shows heterogeneous enhancement on the THRIVE image and higher signal intensity than is typical for normal liver on the DW image. On the ADC map, the hepatic parenchyma turns dark to a similar degree as the spleen <i>(Spl)</i>, a finding that suggests diffusion restriction reflecting cirrhotic changes.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig13c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig14a.jpeg" height="608" width="963" aria-labelledby="fig14a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14a</span> Detection of recurrent sarcoma with DW imaging in an 11-year-old boy with a history of left nephrectomy for undifferentiated renal sarcoma. Axial T2-weighted image <b>(a)</b> and DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b> show a recurrent lobulated tumor in the left renal fossa (arrow). The lesion is much better seen on the DW image than on the T2-weighted image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig14a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig14b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig14b.jpeg" height="608" width="912" aria-labelledby="fig14b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 14b</span> Detection of recurrent sarcoma with DW imaging in an 11-year-old boy with a history of left nephrectomy for undifferentiated renal sarcoma. Axial T2-weighted image <b>(a)</b> and DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b> show a recurrent lobulated tumor in the left renal fossa (arrow). The lesion is much better seen on the DW image than on the T2-weighted image.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig14b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig15a.jpeg" height="662" width="937" aria-labelledby="fig15a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15a</span> Tumor characterization with DW imaging. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(a)</b> and ADC map <b>(b)</b> obtained in a 4-year-old boy with a history of partial resection of retroperitoneal neuroblastoma show residual tumor with restricted diffusion (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(c)</b> and ADC map <b>(d)</b> obtained in a 7-year-old boy show a paraspinal ganglioneuroblastoma (arrows). Overall, the tumor is not diffusion restricted, with moderate signal intensity on the DW image and moderate hyperintensity on the ADC map. <sub><b>*</b></sub> = mild diffusion restriction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig15a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig15b.jpeg" height="662" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig15b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15b</span> Tumor characterization with DW imaging. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(a)</b> and ADC map <b>(b)</b> obtained in a 4-year-old boy with a history of partial resection of retroperitoneal neuroblastoma show residual tumor with restricted diffusion (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(c)</b> and ADC map <b>(d)</b> obtained in a 7-year-old boy show a paraspinal ganglioneuroblastoma (arrows). Overall, the tumor is not diffusion restricted, with moderate signal intensity on the DW image and moderate hyperintensity on the ADC map. <sub><b>*</b></sub> = mild diffusion restriction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig15b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig15c.jpeg" height="469" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig15c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15c</span> Tumor characterization with DW imaging. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(a)</b> and ADC map <b>(b)</b> obtained in a 4-year-old boy with a history of partial resection of retroperitoneal neuroblastoma show residual tumor with restricted diffusion (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(c)</b> and ADC map <b>(d)</b> obtained in a 7-year-old boy show a paraspinal ganglioneuroblastoma (arrows). Overall, the tumor is not diffusion restricted, with moderate signal intensity on the DW image and moderate hyperintensity on the ADC map. <sub><b>*</b></sub> = mild diffusion restriction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig15c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig15d" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig15d.jpeg" height="469" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig15d" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 15d</span> Tumor characterization with DW imaging. <b>(a, b)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 600 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(a)</b> and ADC map <b>(b)</b> obtained in a 4-year-old boy with a history of partial resection of retroperitoneal neuroblastoma show residual tumor with restricted diffusion (arrows). <b>(c, d)</b> Axial DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(c)</b> and ADC map <b>(d)</b> obtained in a 7-year-old boy show a paraspinal ganglioneuroblastoma (arrows). Overall, the tumor is not diffusion restricted, with moderate signal intensity on the DW image and moderate hyperintensity on the ADC map. <sub><b>*</b></sub> = mild diffusion restriction.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig15d">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig16a.jpeg" height="614" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig16a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16a</span> Crohn disease in a 15-year-old boy. Axial postcontrast T1-weighted volume-interpolated breath-hold examination (VIBE) image (Siemens Medical Systems, Erlangen, Germany) <b>(a)</b>, DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b>, and ADC map <b>(c)</b> show an inflamed bowel loop in the pelvis (arrows). The loop is enhanced and mildly thickened on the VIBE image. The bowel wall shows diffusion restriction. In addition, prominent lymph nodes around the inflamed bowel loop are well seen on the DW image (arrowheads in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig16a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig16b.jpeg" height="665" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig16b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16b</span> Crohn disease in a 15-year-old boy. Axial postcontrast T1-weighted volume-interpolated breath-hold examination (VIBE) image (Siemens Medical Systems, Erlangen, Germany) <b>(a)</b>, DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b>, and ADC map <b>(c)</b> show an inflamed bowel loop in the pelvis (arrows). The loop is enhanced and mildly thickened on the VIBE image. The bowel wall shows diffusion restriction. In addition, prominent lymph nodes around the inflamed bowel loop are well seen on the DW image (arrowheads in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig16b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig16c" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig16c.jpeg" height="665" width="938" aria-labelledby="fig16c" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 16c</span> Crohn disease in a 15-year-old boy. Axial postcontrast T1-weighted volume-interpolated breath-hold examination (VIBE) image (Siemens Medical Systems, Erlangen, Germany) <b>(a)</b>, DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b>, and ADC map <b>(c)</b> show an inflamed bowel loop in the pelvis (arrows). The loop is enhanced and mildly thickened on the VIBE image. The bowel wall shows diffusion restriction. In addition, prominent lymph nodes around the inflamed bowel loop are well seen on the DW image (arrowheads in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig16c">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17a" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig17a.jpeg" height="640" width="846" aria-labelledby="fig17a" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17a</span> Tubo-ovarian abscess in a 14-year-old girl. Axial postcontrast T1-weighted image <b>(a)</b> and DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b> show inflammatory changes in the pelvis with a diffusion-restricted abscess (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig17a">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="fig17b" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.343135047/asset/images/large/rg.343135047.fig17b.jpeg" height="640" width="828" aria-labelledby="fig17b" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><span class="heading">Figure 17b</span> Tubo-ovarian abscess in a 14-year-old girl. Axial postcontrast T1-weighted image <b>(a)</b> and DW image (<i>b</i> = 800 sec/mm<sup>2</sup>) <b>(b)</b> show inflammatory changes in the pelvis with a diffusion-restricted abscess (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.343135047&amp;id=fig17b">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="r1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Mürtz P, Flacke S, Träber F, van den Brink JS, Gieseke J, Schild HH. Abdomen: diffusion-weighted MR imaging with pulse-triggered single-shot sequences. <em>Radiology</em> 2002;224(1):258–264.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1148/radiol.2241011117">Crossref</a></div><div class="core-xlink-pubmed"><a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/12091693/">PubMed</a></div><div class="core-xlink-google-scholar"><a href="https://scholar.google.com/scholar_lookup?title=Abdomen%3A+diffusion-weighted+MR+imaging+with+pulse-triggered+single-shot+sequences&amp;author=P+M%C3%BCrtz&amp;author=S+Flacke&amp;author=F+Tr%C3%A4ber&amp;author=JS+van+den+Brink&amp;author=J+Gieseke&amp;author=HH+Schild&amp;publication_year=2002&amp;journal=Radiology&amp;pages=258-264&amp;doi=10.1148%2Fradiol.2241011117&amp;pmid=12091693">Google Scholar</a></div></div></div></div></div><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">2.</div><div id="r2" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content">Koh DM, Collins DJ. Diffusion-weighted MRI in the body: applications and challenges in oncology. <em>AJR Am J Roentgenol</em> 2007;188(6):1622–1635.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossre